\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the past few years, the number of applications that use RFID has
 increased, and their number will potentially further grow in the near future.
 One of its main applications is logistics, where, for example, many tags
 (transponders) may be closely placed on pallets.
 Thus, in such systems, we have a single RFID reader that is responsible
 for identifying an unknown number of tags in the reading area as shown
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:RFID-System"

\end_inset

.
 This naturally requires fast RFID readers (interrogators), in order not
 to slow down the delivery process of the actual goods.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EPC_1,EPC_2,EPC_3"

\end_inset

, the EPCglobal C1 G2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "standard"

\end_inset

 is the most commonly used RFID standards in logistics.
 It is based on Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA), which leads to a certain
 probability of tag-collisions on the communications channel.
 Owing to their low price and simple design, tags can neither sense the
 channel nor communicate with the others.
 Hence, the readers are responsible for coordinating the network, and avoiding
 collisions using anti-collision algorithms.
 
